The first-generation Taurus was launched in 1986 to strong fanfare and sales, replacing the slow-selling LTD. Upon the Taurus' debut, Ford was producing a range of rear-wheel drive cars, as [[Chrysler]] and [[General Motors]] offered more front-wheel drive vehicles. With the introduction of the [[Ford Tempo|Tempo]], Ford had started its own transition to front-wheel drive. The Taurus displayed a rounder shape than its contemporaries, often likened to a '[[jelly bean]]' or 'flying potato',<ref name = "jellybean">{{cite web | last = Schneiderman | first = R.M. | date = [[2006-10-27]] | publisher = Forbes | url = http://www.forbes.com/facesinthenews/2006/10/27/ford-taurus-demise-cx_rs_1027autofacescan01.html | title = Ford Taurus, R.I.P.| accessdate = 2007-06-29}}</ref> inspired by the design of the [[Audi 100#C3, 1983–92|Audi 5000]] and Ford's own Tempo. The aerodynamic design of the Taurus was not purely cosmetic, however. Its aerodynamic shape made the car more fuel efficient, allowing Ford to meet the more stringent [[Corporate Average Fuel Economy]] (CAFE) standards applied by the [[United States]] government.<ref name = "Taub"/> The Taurus' success ultimately led to an American [[automobile design]] revolution; Chrysler and General Motors developed aerodynamic cars in order to capitalize on the Taurus' success.<ref name="Taub"/>

The Taurus and Sable used flush aerodynamic composite [[headlights]], and were the first mainstream sedans from a U.S. automaker to use the new lights. Instead of a conventional [[grille]], the Taurus had a front panel to adopt a grille-less 'bottom breather' nose, first pioneered by the [[Citroën DS]] in the 1950s, and also used briefly on the Mustang. Some special performance models were fitted with additional ventilation openings. The Sable twin had a wraparound "lightbar" with two headlights and a low-wattage stretch in between. The doors went into the roof, and the handles were recessed. The Taurus also had large glass areas, which were flushed into the body, not recessed. 

The interior was available with bucket seats, a rare feature for most American mid-size sedans at the time, and the [[dashboard]] wrapped around the driver and flowed into the door panels to create more of a "cockpit" feel.<ref name = "bestselling"/> The interior contained many innovations, such as a storage box on the rear shelf,<ref name = "G1" /> seats designed to provide maximum comfort for their occupant no matter what position they were in,<ref name = "Taub" /> and a rear seat that was raised slightly higher than the front seat so rear passengers could see the road ahead of them.<ref name = "Taub" />

[[Image:89-91 Ford Taurus wagon.jpg|thumb|left|1989-1991 Ford Taurus wagon]]

The Taurus originally came in four models, MT-5, L, GL, and LX. The MT-5 and L models were basic, starting at [[USD|US$]]10,500, with the GL offering a few interior upgrades like rear headrests and a folding armrest, as well as the standard 3.0&nbsp;litre V6.<ref name = "bestselling" /> The LX was loaded with [[air conditioning]], [[power window]]s, power seats, electric door locks, a cassette stereo and [[cruise control]], although these features were also available as options on the other cars. The top-of-the-line LX [[station wagon]] sold for $14,300.<ref name = "bestselling" />

For 1986, the engines were a 90&nbsp;horsepower (67&nbsp;kW) 2.5&nbsp;litre ''[[Ford HSC engine|HSC]]'' four-cylinder found in the [[Manual transmission|MT-5]] and L models or a new 140&nbsp;horsepower (104&nbsp;kW) 3.0&nbsp;litre [[Ford Vulcan engine|Vulcan]] [[V6 engine|V6]], optional on the L and standard on the GL and LX models. The MT-5 was equipped with a five-speed [[manual transmission]], Vulcan models used a newly-designed four-speed [[Ford AXOD transmission|AXOD]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]], while HSC-equipped cars used the 3-speed [[Ford ATX transmission|ATX]] automatic. Ford's 3.8&nbsp;litre [[Ford Essex V6 engine (Canadian)|Essex]] [[V6 engine|V6]] was added to the lineup in 1988. Although the power output was rated at the same 140&nbsp;horsepower (104&nbsp;kW) as the 3.0&nbsp;litre engine, this V6 produced 215&nbsp;ft•lbf (291&nbsp;N•m) of [[torque]]. However, the 3.8 is known for premature failure of [[head gasket]]s.<ref name = "bestselling" />

In 1990, the interior received a facelift, incorporating a new [[steering wheel]] design with an [[airbag]], a new [[gear shift]]er and a new [[dashboard]] with a new instrument panel.<ref name = "G1" /> The 2.5&nbsp;litre four was given [[sequential fuel injection]], increasing power by 15&nbsp;horsepower (11.2&nbsp;kW) and torque by 10&nbsp;ft•lbf (13.6&nbsp;N•m), as did the 3.0&nbsp;litre V6, although output remained the same for that engine.<ref name = "Engines" /> All but the SHO were fitted with a four-speed automatic for 1990 and a new electronic [[Ford AXOD-E transmission|AXOD-E]] transmission in 1991. LX cars were also fitted with [[anti-lock brake]]s as standard that year.<ref name = "bestselling"/>

===First generation SHO===
[[Image:Taurus-SHO-2.jpg|thumb|left|Ford Taurus SHO with the "Plus" package]]

In 1989, Ford added the performance-oriented SHO model, which stands for "Super High Output".<ref name = "G1" /> This was substantiated by a [[Ford SHO V6 engine|Yamaha 3.0 L]] [[V6]] that made 220 hp and 200 ft·lbf.  Although Ford's reasons for creating the SHO are unclear, it is best known that it was created to use up engines that were meant for a competitor for the [[Toyota MR2]] and [[Pontiac Fiero]] that was shelved in the middle of development.<ref name="SHONTELL">{{cite web|url=http://www.fordmuscle.com/archives/2005/08/SHOnTell/|title=SHO n Tell|publisher=Jon Mikelonis and Matt Wilder|accessdate=2006-07-28}}</ref> As a result, Ford initially advertised the SHO as a limited production vehicle.<ref>{{cite video | people = Ford Motor Company | title = 1989 Ford Taurus SHO commercial | publisher = Ford Motor Company | url = http://www.retrojunk.com/details_commercial/4176/ | date = [[2007-07-19]]}}</ref> However, the SHO turned out to be more successful than Ford had expected, and production continued after 1989.<ref name = "SHONTELL" />

The SHO differed from the normal Taurus on the exterior by having different bumpers, side cladding, fog lamps, and a rear spoiler. The interior also differed, with sports seats and an 8000&nbsp;rpm [[tachometer]]. The SHO became the only Taurus to feature a [[manual transmission]] since the MT5 was discontinued in that year.<ref name = "G1">{{cite web |url=http://www.taurusclub.com/encyclopedia/G1/index.html |title=Generation 1 Spotter's Guide |publisher=Taurus/Sable Encyclopedia |publisher= Taurus Car Club of America |date= |accessdate=2007-02-13}}</ref>

A special edition of the SHO called the Plus package became available in 1991. It came as part of option package #212A and contained different styling cues from the standard SHO, including a plastic 'Power Bulge' hood, a plastic spoiler without the 3rd brake light, 24V V6 badges, body colored molding, non-painted mirrors, body color TAURUS badge, and non-SHO 'slicer' wheels.  There were two special sub-options to the Plus package: White painted cars came with white painted wheels, and a plus exclusive Jade Green (sometimes called Deep Jade Green) was available only in 1991.<ref name="shotimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.shotimes.com/php-bin/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0&sid=20|title=The 1991 SHO "Plus" Option|publisher=SHOTIMES mailing list|accessdate=2006-05-16}}</ref>

==Second generation (1992–1995)==
{{Infobox Automobile generation
| name = Second generation
| image = [[Image:91-95 Ford Taurus sedan.jpg|250px|Ford Taurus sedan]]
